      <p class = 'right'>Although the U.S. government does not have adequate data for the total number of foreign employmers working in America, it is estimated that there are roughly <strong>1.42 million</strong> temporary foreign workers who are authorized to be employed in the U.S. labor market. That number is approximately equal to <strong>1%</strong> of the U.S. labor force. Perhaps the H-1B visa does not matter much to 99% people in the labor force, but to the other 1% who need some kind of work visa as work authorization, <strong>H-1B</strong> visa is the most popular path to do so, accounting for more than <strong>32%</strong> of total work visa issued in the United States.</p>
    </div>

    <div class = 'step'>
      <img src = "images/cap.jpg" style='width:600px;margin:0 auto;'>
      <p style='max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;font-size:16px;text-align:justify;'>But getting a work visa in the first place is never easy. Since the H-1B was created in 1990s, Congress has limited the number of H-1Bs made available each year. As of now, the current annual numerical limit "cap" is 65,000 visas, with an addition of 20,000 H-1B visas for foreign professionals who graduate with a master’s degree or doctorate from a U.S. institution of higher learning.</p>
    </div>

