    <div class ='tb' style ='text-align:right;font-size:14px;'>
    <p>But over the years, USCIS has received more petitions than there are visa numbers available as there are always a greater number of skilled workers applying for the H-1B visas.</p>
    <p>So what happen when the number of applications exceeds the yearly quota? USCIS would conduct a lottery to determine which employers’ petitions for H-1B workers will be processed. Yes, pure luck. </p>
    <p>However, even if the applicant get drawn, it does not guarantee for approval by the USCIS. There is a chance that the USCIS will issue A Request For Evidence (RFE) to the applicants to provie additional supporting materials for their applications, and in the worst case, a rejection would be issued. </p>
    <p>Okay, but let's not forget, to qualify for the H-1B application, first the worker needs an employer sponsorship, which is not easy to get for some young professions or people working in certain industries. </p>
